[caption id="attachment_339" align="alignleft" width="300"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-339" src="http://digitalhistory.acs.unr.edu/hist300a/sp2017/group1/wp-content/uploads/sites/19/2017/10/Charles-Gallagher-studio_NHS-300x300.jpg" alt="Black and white photograph of building" width="300" height="300" /> The C. D. Gallagher Studio[/caption]

<div class="SubCatTextDiv" style="margin-top: 20px">

<strong>Charles Gallagher</strong> <em>(1884-1977) was a photographer in McGill, Nevada, during World War II and recalled the removal to internment camps of his Japanese neighbors. Gallagher was interviewed by Mary Ellen Glass in 1965.</em>

</div>
&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;
<h2 class="firstHeading">Transcript</h2>
<div class="SubCatTextDiv">

When the Japanese came in to McGill, they formed their own communities. They didn't have a social life like the other foreign people had, but they did have their own communities. There were a good many of them who did not speak English. There was quite a number of them. I'd guess that they [the Japanese] outnumbered any other nationality for the unskilled labor corps at McGill when the second World War broke out, then they were all interned. Most of them shipped out of the community to the internment camps, mostly down in Oregon and California. As a group, they never returned, but a great many of the individual Japanese did, and they became very good, very desirable citizens.

</div>
<div></div>
