[caption id="attachment_960" align="alignleft" width="234"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-960" src="http://digitalhistory.acs.unr.edu/hist300a/sp2017/group1/wp-content/uploads/sites/19/2017/10/smilg-234x300.jpg" alt="Image of Art Smith" width="234" height="300" /> Art Smith[/caption]

<div class="SubCatTextDiv" style="margin-top: 20px"><strong>Art Smith</strong><em> (1922-1999) was born in Sparks, Nevada, and later moved to Las Vegas to work at the Bank of Nevada, where he was responsible for residential loans during the 1950s. He rose through the ranks in the banking industry and retired in 1984 as chairman and chief officer of First Interstate Bank of Nevada. Smith was interviewed by R.T. King in 1996</em></div>
&nbsp;
</br></br></br></br></br></br></br></br>
<h2 class="firstHeading">Transcript</h2>
<div class="SubCatTextDiv">
During World War II, thousands of Southern blacks had come to Las Vegas to work for Basic Magnesium and other war industries. The Westside, where they settled, experienced explosive growth. It soon became the largest black community in the state, but not many black people came to the bank asking for credit. [Mr. Smith worked as an assistant cashier and loan officer at the Bank of Nevada in Las Vegas during the 1950s.] If they did and they qualified, they got the money—our bank never discriminated on the basis of race in the loans it was making. The problem was, very few blacks were qualified to borrow, and the reasons had nothing to do with color.</div>
&nbsp;
<div class="audioFormat">

[audio mp3="http://digitalhistory.acs.unr.edu/hist300a/sp2017/group1/wp-content/uploads/sites/19/2017/10/SmithH1.mp3"][/audio]

</div>
<h2 class="firstHeading">Transcript</h2>
<div class="SubCatTextDiv">
<div class="audioText">The black people in the old days, in those days, were treated poorly because of their race and their color. I never heard anything about that. Nobody ever told me that you don’t loan to them because they’re black people. I think I told you that I would call these friends of mine, and even when their own people won’t vouch for them, I mean . . . .
&nbsp;
<strong>Listen, we were having a conversation off the tape, and you gave me some reasons why you would not loan to them that had nothing to do with color. Maybe you can talk about those now.</strong>
&nbsp;
Well, you want to talk about a house loan, a real estate loan [for] a place to live. In those days, the houses that they lived in had no collateral value—I mean, the only real value there was the lot that they sat on—and there was no way you could justify making a real estate loan like that [without collateral]. Our own government wouldn’t make an FHA loan over there [on the Westside]. If you're an average lending officer, and the government says “We won't make any FHA loans over there,” what are you going to think about making a conventional loan?
&nbsp;
<strong>Oh, that’s remarkable. I didn’t know that, that the government would not make FHA loans.</strong>
&nbsp;
Well, the FHA goes only where they want to go—they won't go just any place.
&nbsp;
<strong>And in the forties and fifties, the FHA was not making loans on the Westside?</strong>
&nbsp;
Not on the Westside.
&nbsp;
<strong>I’ll be damned. I was totally unaware of that.</strong>
&nbsp;
But oh, there was some good people. I finally remembered that the two people that took good care of the [unclear] was Kate and Dave, Katie and Dave. And they were really fine people. And there was that Jodi Cannon [sp?] that I talked about. I forget, there was a bishop for one of the black churches over there, a big man. But you could always talk to him, and he’d tell you the straight scoop. But besides not having collateral that they could put up for a loan, there was really not much background on them.
&nbsp;
You’d say, “What’s your name?” and they’d give you their name.
&nbsp;
“Where do you live, and where are you from?”
&nbsp;
“I’m from Louisiana.”
&nbsp;
And that was about it. I mean, I really—all my years in the banking business, I’ve never heard ever once anything discriminatory about those people.
&nbsp;
<strong>You talked a little bit also about the types of jobs, the kind of employment most of them would have. Do you want to discuss that?</strong>
&nbsp;
Well, you know, by nature of their education they can’t get the top jobs. There’s some who have the top jobs and they’re excellent, but the average guy, washing dishes at Caesars Palace or digging a trench, or . . . I mean, not being disrespectful, but those are not the jobs where longevity and these sorts of things seem to bring any stability to you.
</div>
<p style="text-align: center">***End of Audio***</p>
&nbsp;
Nonetheless, Bank of Nevada would lend money to anyone who could qualify, and some blacks could. I personally knew a few who came in for loans, and I could check out the others by calling a businessman I knew over on the Westside. I'd say, "You know so-and-so?"
&nbsp;
"Yeah, I know him."
&nbsp;
"He wants to borrow a hundred dollars. What do you think?"
&nbsp;
If the guy wasn't a good credit risk, he might say, "Well now, Mr. Smitty, I guess I don't know him that well. I guess we're talking about two different guys." But if the guy was OK, he'd say, "I'd trust him with anything."
&nbsp;
I believed that if you made a loan, you ought to be able to collect it. Once I had a delinquent loan, and I went over to the Westside to collect it. Art Smith, bold young assistant cashier! [laughter] I rang and rang the doorbell, and I knocked on the door, and I went next door to ask the neighbors. No answer at either place; nothing. And it was quiet—nobody could be seen anywhere in the neighborhood.
&nbsp;
As I'm getting in my car to leave, a guy comes driving around the corner and accidentally hits a dog that's out in the street. The dog lets out a yip and a squeal, and every front door on that whole block opens, and people stick their heads out. Everybody was home, and they probably hoped I'd been run over. [laughter] It finally got to the point that we wouldn't let our collectors go over to the Westside because we didn't think it was safe for them. There was that much animosity. We would use a collection agency instead.

</div>
<div></div>
</br>
